                        <summary>
                            <p>The four subjoined inscriptions are written in modern Tamil characters and record “the perpetual devotion”<note><foreign>catācervai</foreign> seems to represent the Sanskrit <foreign>sadā-sevā</foreign>. It is here used in the sense of “a monument of perpetual devotion,” just as, in Sanskrit, <foreign>kīrti</foreign> and <foreign>kīrtana</foreign> have sometimes the meaning “a monument of fame;” see Mr. Fleet's <hi rend="italic">Corpus Inscriptionum Indicarum</hi>, Vol. III, p. 212, note 6.</note> of a certain <hi rend="bold">Chandra-piḷḷai</hi> of <hi rend="bold">Kāṭṭeri</hi>.</p>
                            
                            <p>There are several similar inscriptions in other parts of the temple, viz., two on the pedestals of the two <foreign>dvārapālakas</foreign> in front of the <foreign>gopura</foreign>, one on the left outer wall of the inner <foreign>prākāra</foreign>, and five on the floor of the <foreign>alaṁkāra-maṇḍapa</foreign>, of which two are written in Tamil, two in Telugu, and one in very faint Nāgarī characters.</p>
                        </summary>
                    </msContents>
